    <h1>Port of LA drayage guide</h1>
    <p class="CardLabel">Yard congestion, chassis pools, TWIC checks — the full playbook.</p>

    <p>The Port of LA + Long Beach moves ~25M TEUs a year — about a third of US import volume. Drayage looks simple from the outside (truck container in, truck container out) but it's gated by 5 things that catch new operators flat-footed.</p>

    <h2 class="CardTitle">1. TWIC card</h2>
    <p>Transportation Worker Identification Credential. Federally required for terminal access. ~$125 fee, 6-week processing. Without one you cannot get past the gate.</p>

    <h2 class="CardTitle">2. Chassis pool membership</h2>
    <p>POLA/POLB don't supply chassis. You either own/lease or are a member of a pool (FlexiVan, DCLI, TRAC). Pool membership is the cheapest entry point at ~$0/day rental but $25-$50/day if you keep it past free time.</p>

    <h2 class="CardTitle">3. eModal &amp; PortDrayage appointment systems</h2>
    <p>Every terminal uses an appointment platform. Same-day appointments are gold. Show up without one and you may sit 4-6 hours. We use eModal for APM Terminals and Pier 400 and have appointment alerts auto-text our drivers.</p>

    <h2 class="CardTitle">4. Yard congestion</h2>
    <p>Tuesday/Thursday afternoon are worst. Best bet: 4am-8am or 8pm-midnight. Wolfs schedules half our drayage off-peak.</p>

    <h2 class="CardTitle">5. Pre-pull strategy</h2>
    <p>Pull from terminal to your yard, decouple, deliver to consignee on a separate run. Better truck utilization, lower demurrage risk.</p>

